The first task is to cut the pyramid into right pyramids with triangular bases.  Our starting shape (the hexagonal pyramid) has height, base area, and volume\[h = \sqrt{3^2 - \sqrt{3^2 - 1^2}^2} = \sqrt{6}, \quad A = 6 \cdot \frac{1}{2} \cdot 2 \sqrt{3} \cdot 1 = 6 \sqrt{3},\]and\[V = \frac{1}{3} \cdot 6 \sqrt{3} \cdot \sqrt{6} = 2 \sqrt{18}.\]Since we know height and volume, we can find base area of these smaller pyramids.  The six right pyramids each have volume $\tfrac{1}{6} V = \tfrac{1}{3} \sqrt{3}$ and height $\tfrac{1}{2} h = \sqrt{3/2}$.  Then we solve\[A = \frac{2V}{h} = \frac{2\sqrt{3}/6}{\sqrt{3}/2} = 1,\]which is exactly what we would expect for pyramids whose base is a 30-60-90 triangle.  Edges of this 30-60-90 triangle have length ratio $1:\sqrt{3}:2$, so the base in our case has side length 1, the height of the base has length $\sqrt{3}$, and the slant height of the base has length 2.

