The line first hits $AB,$ forming a right triangle (shaded) with area $\frac{1}{2} \cdot AX' \cdot X'B$ for some point $X' \in AB.$ Labelling $X$ as the foot of the perpendicular from $B$ to $CD,$ the area of this triangle is $\frac{1}{2} \cdot BC \cdot BX = \frac{1}{2} \cdot \sqrt{5} \cdot 1 = \frac{\sqrt{5}}{2},$ which is less than $2.$ After the line passes $B,$ it forms a trapezoid with $AX$ as the height and the distance $BX'$ as the average of the bases. If this area is less than $2$ then the area of the triangle formed when the line passes $X$ is the same as the area of the first triangle, $\frac{\sqrt{5}}{2} < 2,$ and so we will not have gone far enough. Thus we only need to check whether we pass through $BX$ before the trapezoid has area $2.$ The base lengths change from $BC$ to $AC$ as $BX'$ changes from $1$ to $2$ so the area of the trapezoid is \[\frac{1}{2} \cdot 2 \cdot \frac{AC+BC}{2}= AC+BC = \sqrt{10} + \sqrt{5} > 2.\] Therefore the line intersects the segment $BX$ (not just the line) and so we just need to find out where in order to find where it intersects $\overline{CD}.$ The area of the trapezoid is increasing linearly as $BX'$ goes from $1$ to $2,$ and moreover is $\sqrt{10} + \sqrt{5}<2$ when $BX'=1$ and is $\sqrt{10} + \sqrt{2 \sqrt{5}}+ \sqrt{5} > 2$ when $BX' = 1 + .01$ so should pass $2$ when $BX'$ is close to $1.$ Solve \[\frac{1+BX'}{2} \left( \sqrt{5} + \sqrt{BX'} \right) = 2\] for $BX',$ telling us where we are on $\overline{AB},$ and then use similar triangles to find $CX'.$ Plugging into WolframAlpha, we find $BX' \approx 1.1347$ and so \[\frac{BC}{AC} = \frac{BX'}{AX'} \approx 1.1347\] and solving gives $AX' \approx 1.4753.$ Then by similar triangles $CX' = AX' \cdot \frac{CX}{AX} \approx 1.4753 \cdot \frac{3}{1} \approx \boxed{4.43}.$

