When a triangle has a fixed base length of $d$, it is maximized with the greatest possible height, or a height that extends to the very edge of the circle.

The height of this triangle is a radius of the circle, or $10\text{ cm}$. Hence, the base of the triangle is $2\times10=20\text{ cm}$. The area of the triangle is $\frac12(d)(h)=\frac{1}{2}(20)(10)=\boxed{100}$ square centimeters.

