Draw the circle with center $A$ and radius $1$, and the circle with center $B$ and radius $1$.  The area of this region is $2\cdot\frac12\pi = \pi$, containing one circle.  The two circles also intersect in two points, their intersection having the shape of a "lens," consisting of two circular segments, one from each circle.  The area of a circular segment is $\frac12r^2\theta - \frac12r^2\sin\theta$, where $\theta$ is the angle subtended by the segment.  The circular segment here has $\theta=\frac{\pi}3$, so the area of this "lens" is $2\cdot\left[\frac12\cdot1^2\cdot\frac{\pi}3 - \frac12\cdot1^2\cdot\sin \frac{\pi}3\right] = \frac{\pi}3 - \frac{\sqrt{3}}2$.  Therefore the union of all disks covering $\overline{AB}$ has area $\pi + \frac{\pi}3 - \frac{\sqrt{3}}2 = \boxed{\frac43\pi - \frac{\sqrt{3}}2}$.

