When $\triangle ABC$ is rotated about leg $BC$ to create a cylinder, the volume is $\frac{1}{3}(4)(9) = 12$ cubic cm. However when the triangle is rotated about $AB$ to create a cone, the volume is $\pi \cdot 2^2 \cdot 4 = 16\pi,$ or about $50$ cubic cm. The volume when rotated about $AC$ will be the difference of the two, or $50 - 12 = 38$, since the areas rotate the same around the $AC$ axis. Thus the greatest possible volume is $\boxed{50}$ cubic centimeters.

