Since triangles $ABC$ and $OBC$ share the same altitude from $B$, the ratio of their areas is equal to the ratio of their bases, which is the ratio of the circumradius of $ABC$ to the circumradius of $OBC$.  Recall that $AB = 5$ and $BC = 6$. This makes $ABC$ isosceles, so we can divide it into two $3 - 4 - 5$ right triangles. This shows us the altitude to $BC$ has length $4$, so the area of $ABC$ is $12$.

