Because $\triangle ABC$ is a right triangle, the median drawn to the hypotenuse is the line segment connecting $B$ to the midpoint $M$ of $AC,$ shown above. By the Pythagorean Theorem, $AC=\sqrt{2^2+(4\sqrt{2})^2}=4\sqrt{3}.$ Therefore, $AM=MC=4\sqrt{3}/2=2\sqrt{3}.$ Since $AB=4\sqrt{2}$, $AD=DB=4\sqrt{2}/2=2\sqrt{2}.$ Using the Pythagorean Theorem to find length $BD$ gives us $BD=\sqrt{(2\sqrt{3})^2+(2\sqrt{2})^2}=4\sqrt{2}/2=\boxed{2\sqrt{2}}.$

Note that the length of the median of a right triangle to the hypotenuse is always half the length of the hypotenuse.

