Nine $40^\circ$ arcs lie on the perimeter of $S$.  We know the formula $2 \pi r \cdot \frac{\theta}{360^\circ}$ for the length of an arc of a circle with radius $r$, so the sum of the nine $40^\circ$ arcs not on the perimeter is $(9)\left( 2 \pi (1)\cdot\frac{40^\circ}{360^\circ}\right) = \frac{\pi}{2}$.

To find the distance between any two adjacent $40^\circ$ arcs, first draw a 36-72-72 triangle with base on the perimeter of the nonagon. Let the segment from an apex of a 36-72-72 triangle to the midpoints of its base be the apothem.  If the nonagon's side length is 2, then the base $AB$ of the 36-72-72 triangle is 2.  Thus, $AO=OB=\sqrt{\left(\frac{4}{\sin 36^\circ}\right)^2-1}$.  We apply the Law of Sines to get $AO=\frac{4}{\sin 36^\circ}$ which is approximately $6.1818$ then the length of $AB$ is approximately $5$.   Therefore, the side length of $S$ is approximately 3 because $AO$                        is approximately 6.  It's also helpful to note that $\frac{\pi}{2}$ is approximately $1.57$. Adding the perimeter of nonagon $(9)\left(2\right)$ to the total sum of the $40^\circ$ arcs and the distances between them $(18)\left(1\right)$ gives $18+18+1.57=\boxed{37.57}$.

A trapezoid's area is equal to the sum of its bases divided by two, times its height.  Let the other base have length $x$; we can set up the following equation: \begin{align*}
\frac{16+x}{2}\times 12 &= 162\\
\Rightarrow \qquad 8+x &= \frac{162}{12}=13.5
\end{align*} Solving, we find that the other base has length $x=5.5\text{ cm}$.

[asy]
draw((0,0)--(0,12)--(11,12)--(16,0)--cycle);
label("12 cm",(-1,6),W);
label("x=5.5 cm",(5.5,13),N);
draw((0.8,0)--(0.8,0.8)--(0,.8));
draw((0,11.2)--(0.8,11.2)--(0.8,12));
label("16 cm",(8,-1),S);
draw((0,12)--(0,21)--(0,0)--(5.5,0)--(16,0),linewidth(0.3));
draw((0,12)--(5.5,12)--(16,12),linewidth(0.3));
label("$l$",(0,16),W);
label("$16-5.5=10.5$",(2,0),S);
[/asy] We see that the trapezoid is divided into a $12\text{ cm}$-by-$5.5\text{ cm}$ rectangle and a right triangle with legs of lengths $12\text{ cm}$ and $10.5\text{ cm}$.  The hypotenuse of this right triangle, $l$, is the other side of the trapezoid we lack, so using the Pythagorean Theorem, we find that it's equal to $\sqrt{(12^2+{10.5^2})\text{ cm}}=\sqrt{198}\text{ cm}=3\sqrt{22}\text{ cm}$. The perimeter is equal to $16+5.5+2\times(3\sqrt{22})\text{ cm}=\boxed{21.5+6\sqrt{22}}$ centimeters.

Each right angle of $ABC$ is halved by drawing a square.  Call the sides which are bisected $AB$ and $BC$.  Call the side of the square $s$ and $AB=t.$

The triangles formed are similar ($45-45-90\times 2$), so we can use rise-over-run to find a relationship between $AB,$ $BC$ and the side of the square: \[
\frac{s}{t}=\frac{s}{t-s}
\]

So $s=t-s,$ so the the length of the hypotenuse, AC, is $2s$.  AC is also the diameter of the circle which circumscribes triangle $ABC$.  It follows that the side of the square is $\frac{AC}{2}$ and the area of the square is $\frac{AC^2}{4}$.

Therefore, $AC=\sqrt{60}$, and if we draw a square in triangle $DEF$, which is congruent to triangle $ABC$, we will have a square of area which is $\frac{AC^2}{4}$, so the area of the square is $\boxed{\frac{15}{4}}.$

