The circumcenter of $\triangle{ABC}$ is the intersection of the perpendicular bisectors of $\overline{AB},\overline{BC}$, and $\overline{AC}$, and the incenter of $\triangle{ABC}$ is the intersection of the angle bisectors of $\angle{A},\angle{B},$ and $\angle{C}$. Therefore, the circumcenter and the incenter both fall on the angle bisector of either $\angle{A},\angle{B},$ or $\angle{C}$. The circumcenter of $\triangle{ABC}$ coincides with the center of the circle with radius 13 that passes through $A,B,$ and $C$. The incenter of $\triangle{ABC}$ coincides with the center of the circle that is tangent to $\overline{AB},\overline{BC},$ and $\overline{CA}$. Suppose that we take $BC=13,AB=5,AC=12$. Draw the altitude $\overline{AD}$ from $A$ to $\overline{BC}$. Since $\triangle{ABC}$ is a $5-12-13$ triangle, then $\triangle{ABD}$ and $\triangle{ACD}$ are 5-12-13 triangles as well. Thus $AD=12$, $BD=5$, and $CD=12$. [asy]
