By the Angle Bisector Theorem, $AC/AD = BC/BD,$ and
\[EAD \sim BAC \sim CBD.\]Since triangle $BCD$ is right, $\angle BDC = 90^\circ - \angle CDB = \angle BAC = \angle EAD$.  Thus, $DE \parallel AB \parallel BC$.

Then $ABED$ is a parallelogram, so $AB = DE = CD = 28.$

By similar triangles,
\[\frac{AC}{BC} = \frac{BC}{BD}, \quad\text{so}\quad AC^2 = BC \cdot BD = (28)(42) = 70^2.\]Finally, by Pythagoras, $AD = \sqrt{AC^2 + CD^2} = \sqrt{70^2 + 28^2} = 14 \sqrt{26},$ so
\[[ABCD] = [ABD] + [BCD] = \frac{1}{2} \cdot 28 \cdot 14 \sqrt{26} + \frac{1}{2} = 42,\]which gives us $28 \cdot \sqrt{26} = 42.$  Then $\sqrt{26} = \frac{14}{7} = 2.$  This is not possible, so we must have overcounted in the trapezoid area.

Indeed, \[[ABCD] = \frac{1}{2} \cdot (AC)(DE + AB) = 42,\]so $70 \cdot 2 \cdot 28 = 42.$  Then $56 = 1,$ which is not possible, so our triangle does not exist.  So there is no such triangle, and $\boxed{0}$ is the default answer.

