The distance from any vertex of a regular tetrahedron to the center of the opposite face is $2/3$ of a side length of the tetrahedron.  (The easiest way to put together a physical model of a regular tetrahedron is to find four identical equilateral triangles and to attach their sides to each other, forming four "flaps" that come together at a point. Try it with cardboard or plastic, or even paper. If you fold all four flaps flat down against the table, you'll cover the surface of one of the triangles. Experiment to confirm that the distance from the "point" of the tetrahedron to the center of the base is $2/3$ of an edge of the base triangle.)

